Merge pull request #21 from mdcallag/master

Make it faster for MySQL

Use 2 connections per client -- read-write, read-only. This avoids the need
to send "commit" for queries. This also lets InnoDB use its fast-path
for read-only transactions (SELECT when in auto-commit mode). And it reduces
the number of statements that are run (fewer COMMIT calls are made).

Add FORCE_INDEX hint on link range query to keep InnoDB from doing IO
to estimate selectivity on the wrong index.

Update indexes for linktable in README.md. These options reduce disk reads
during IO-bound linkbench.

With these changes I almost doubled QPS.

Differential Revision: https://reviews.facebook.net/D6429

Alter history cache algorithm to reduce skew

Summary:
Previously the way caching worked tended to result in skewed behaviour:
* frequently accessed ids ended up having many cache entries
* entries were never evicted so we often kept reaccessing the very tail of the lists

This commit changes the cache algorithm so that
* There is only one cache entry per (id1, link_type)
* Entries are evicted once the full list has been retrieved

Test Plan: Adapted unit tests to reflect fact that history cache more often empty

Add in support for blending in an uncorrelated

Summary:
We see an imperfect correlation between outdegree and frequency of access
for link reads/writes.  In order to support such partial correlation, this
commit adds support for mixing together a perfectly correlated and perfectly
uncorrelated distribution to choose ids for access.

This can bring down average range scan size to more realistic levels.

Some optional config file entries were added to support this.

Differential Revision: https://reviews.facebook.net/D6009

New Motif data generator

Summary:
Try to generate somewhat more realistic data that has some of the
compressibility properties of real data.  The basic idea is that
a data generator has a set of "motifs" that will repeatedly occur
in the output data.  This is implemented by having an internal buffer of
random data from which fragments are inserted into the output.

Test Plan:

sure that the compreesibility of the output data is being changed in the
way we'd expect as parameters vary.

Test the performance of the data generator to make sure it won't be
a performance bottleneck.  It seems like it is at worse marginally slower
than the uniform data generator, and at best somewhat faster (if there
are many repeated motifs).  In either case it won't be a bottleneck.

Reviewers: dhruba, vamsi

Reviewed By: dhruba

Differential Revision: https://reviews.facebook.net/D5289

Multiple link types for LinkBench

Summary:
Add in config parameter to control number of link types (default to 1 if
not provided).

The number of links per id1 is the same as before the change, but these
links are divided between the n link types.  If we number the link types
1 to n, the links are distributed in a round robin fashion.  E.g. if
there are five types and two links for id1=1234, then there is a link of type 1 and a
link of type 2.  If there are five types, there is a link of each type.

This change makes the count table much bigger.  Switch bulk count add
logic to use "REPLACE INTO" to speed up loading of link counts.

Test Plan:

Summary:

selected.  The pattern of requests is loosely approximated with a

Differential Revision: https://reviews.facebook.net/D4725

Add option to throttle request rate per thread.

Summary:
Simulate poisson process with inter-arrival times exponentially
distributed. Includes unit tests for request rate functionality.

Also work on consolidating random number generation.  The random number
generation in the original implementation creates many Random() instances,
each of which is seeded with the current time at construction time.
This is not really ideal as the Java RNG is fast but not particularly
good quality and the stream of numbers from a single RNG is likely to
be better quality that that from many RNGs with correlated seeds.

Also working towards deterministic random number generation, where
a single initial seed determines the entire request workload. This
allows workloads and tests to be reproducible.  That seed is used for
a high-quality but slow RNG, which then generates seeds for new
faster RNGs that can be passed to threads in such a way that the calls to
each RNG always occur in the same order.  The request workload is now
deterministic except for the id1 selection algorithm in
RealDistribution, which is inherently non-deterministic because it
mutates arrays shared between threads.

Differential Revision: https://reviews.facebook.net/D3927

Work queue model for loaders

Summary:
This diff addresses the tail off in loading throughput towards the
end of the loading process due to skew in the chunk sizes given to the
loader threads. Because of the distribution of links, some chunks of the
id1 space have many more links to load than others.  The most robust
approach I could think of to solve this was to have a smaller pool of
loader threads (~10) and dynamically assign the chunks to threads with
a work queue.  If we break the work up into chunks such that
least work, then all of the threads will likely run out of work at
nearly the same time.

Since the per-thread progress reports aren't meaningful in this model,
I added in a global progress report and have chunk progress reports if
debug logging is turned on.

Differential Revision: https://reviews.facebook.net/D3921

Added in bulk loading capability for LinkBench

Summary:
Instead of loading links one-by-one and updating counts each time,
do inserts with many links, and create the count table with a single
query at the end.

This gives a big speedup: the load completes 5x-6x faster on the small
loads I've tried.  The two changes (batching inserts, and doing the
count table at the end) seem to contribute roughly equally to the
speedup.

I haven't tried to tune the thread count or the batch size yet, so there
could be even bigger gains from that.

Made a couple of other minor changes to code org since it made it easier
to implement the bulk loading
